<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate miles per gallon?", answer: "Divide the total distance traveled (in miles) by the total fuel used (in gallons). For example, if you drove 300 miles on 10 gallons, your MPG is 300 / 10 = 30 MPG. For the most accurate reading, fill your tank completely, reset your trip odometer, drive normally, then fill up again and note how many gallons it took." },
  { question: "What is a good MPG for a car?", answer: "A good MPG depends on vehicle type. For passenger cars, 30-40 MPG is considered good, with hybrids reaching 50-60 MPG. SUVs typically get 25-30 MPG, and trucks 15-25 MPG. The EPA average for all new vehicles in 2024 is about 26 MPG. Electric vehicles equivalent can exceed 100 MPGe." },
  { question: "How do I convert MPG to liters per 100 km?", answer: "To convert MPG (US gallons) to L/100km, divide 235.215 by the MPG value. For example, 30 MPG equals 235.215 / 30 = 7.84 L/100km. This inverse relationship means higher MPG corresponds to lower L/100km, indicating better fuel efficiency in both systems." },
  { question: "Why does my actual MPG differ from the EPA estimate?", answer: "EPA estimates are measured under controlled laboratory conditions. Real-world factors that reduce MPG include aggressive driving and rapid acceleration, highway speeds above 50 mph, cold weather and short trips, heavy cargo or towing, underinflated tires, and excessive idling. Typically, real-world MPG is 10-20% lower than EPA estimates." },
  { question: "Does driving speed affect fuel efficiency?", answer: "Yes, significantly. Most vehicles reach optimal fuel efficiency between 35-55 mph. Above 50 mph, fuel efficiency drops rapidly due to aerodynamic drag, which increases with the square of speed. Driving at 65 mph versus 55 mph can reduce fuel economy by about 15%, and driving at 75 mph can reduce it by about 25%." }
]) %>

